[When I first saw this article and others like it, I was concerned the journalist had mixed up epizootic hemorrhagic disease and bluetongue (BT) virus. These diseases are closely related but clearly and distinctly separate.

I sought out the assistance of a colleague, Dr Jim Logan, Wyoming state veterinarian. He provided me with the following information, which I am sharing with his permission:

Samples were sent to Plum Island Animal Disease Center. Both diseases were tested for and EHD was positive but BT was negative. Tests used were AB-ELISA [antibody-ELISA] for BT, which was negative. AGID [agar gel immunodiffusion] and RT-PCR [reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction] were used for EHD and were positive. Tests were also run for vesicular stomatitis and FMD and were negative.

Nebraska and South Dakota also have found EHD in bovines. I don't know what tests were run, but I believe their samples were also sent to Plum Island Animal Disease Center.

I am grateful for Dr Logan's rapid and helpful response to my queries.

For more information with regard to the differences between EHD and BTV readers are encouraged to read the moderator's comments in ProMED-mail 20120908.1286824

Wyoming may be found on the interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at http://healthmap.org/r/3aGm. - Mod.TG]
